# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-embeddings
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] In data analysis, **cosine similarity** is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors defined in an inner product space.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is the cosine of the angle between the vectors; that is, it is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their lengths.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] It follows that the cosine similarity does not depend on the magnitudes of the vectors, but only on their angle.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The cosine similarity always belongs to the interval $[-1,+1].$ For example, two proportional vectors have a cosine similarity of +1, two orthogonal vectors have a similarity of 0, and two opposite vectors have a similarity of −1.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] In some contexts, the component values of the vectors cannot be negative, in which case the cosine similarity is bounded in $[0,1]$ .
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] For example, in information retrieval and text mining, each word is assigned a different coordinate and a document is represented by the vector of the numbers of occurrences of each word in the document.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity then gives a useful measure of how similar two documents are likely to be, in terms of their subject matter, and independently of the length of the documents.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The technique is also used to measure cohesion within clusters in the field of data mining.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] One advantage of cosine similarity is its low complexity, especially for sparse vectors: only the non-zero coordinates need to be considered.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Other names for cosine similarity include **Orchini similarity** and **Tucker coefficient of congruence**; the **Otsuka–Ochiai similarity** (see below) is cosine similarity applied to binary data.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] where $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are the i th components of vectors $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ , respectively.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The resulting similarity ranges from −1 meaning exactly opposite, to +1 meaning exactly the same, with 0 indicating orthogonality (no correlation), while in-between values indicate intermediate similarity or dissimilarity.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] For text matching, the attribute vectors *A* and *B* are usually the term frequency vectors of the documents.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity can be seen as a method of normalizing document length during comparison.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] In the case of information retrieval, the cosine similarity of two documents will range from $0\to 1$ , since the term frequencies cannot be negative.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] This remains true when using TF-IDF weights.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The angle between two term frequency vectors cannot be greater than 90°.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] If the attribute vectors are normalized by subtracting the vector means (e.g., $A-{\bar {A}}$ ), the measure is called the centered cosine similarity and is equivalent to the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] By virtue of being proportional to squared Euclidean distance, the cosine distance is not a true distance metric; it does not exhibit the triangle inequality property — or, more formally, the Schwarz inequality — and it violates the coincidence axiom.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] To repair the triangle inequality property while maintaining the same ordering, one can convert to Euclidean distance ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2(1-S_{C}(A,B))}}}$ or angular distance *θ* = arccos(*S**C*(*A*, *B*)).
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Alternatively, the triangular inequality that does work for angular distances can be expressed directly in terms of the cosines; see below.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The normalized angle, referred to as **angular distance**, between any two vectors A and B is a formal distance metric and can be calculated from the cosine similarity.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The complement of the angular distance metric can then be used to define **angular similarity** function bounded between 0 and 1, inclusive.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Unfortunately, computing the inverse cosine (arccos) function is slow, making the use of the angular distance more computationally expensive than using the more common (but not metric) cosine distance above.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Another effective proxy for cosine distance can be obtained by $L_{2}$ normalisation of the vectors, followed by the application of normal Euclidean distance.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Using this technique each term in each vector is first divided by the magnitude of the vector, yielding a vector of unit length.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Once the normalisation has occurred, the vector space can be used with the full range of techniques available to any Euclidean space, notably standard dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] This normalised form distance is often used within many deep learning algorithms.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Here, A and B are sets, and $|A|$ is the number of elements in A .
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] If sets are represented as bit vectors, the Otsuka–Ochiai coefficient can be seen to be the same as the cosine similarity.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] It is identical to the score introduced by Godfrey Thomson.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] In a recent book, the coefficient is tentatively misattributed to another Japanese researcher with the family name Otsuka.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The confusion arises because in 1957 Akira Ochiai attributes the coefficient only to Otsuka (no first name mentioned) by citing an article by Ikuso Hamai (Japanese: 浜井 生三), who in turn cites the original 1936 article by Yanosuke Otsuka.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The most noteworthy property of cosine similarity is that it reflects a relative, rather than absolute, comparison of the individual vector dimensions.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] For any positive constant a and vector V , the vectors V and $aV$ are maximally similar.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The measure is thus most appropriate for data where frequency is more important than absolute values; notably, term frequency in documents.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] However more recent metrics with a grounding in information theory, such as Jensen–Shannon, SED, and triangular divergence have been shown to have improved semantics in at least some contexts.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is related to Euclidean distance as follows.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The Euclidean distance is called the *chord distance* (because it is the length of the chord on the unit circle) and it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors which were normalized to unit sum of squared values within them.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] This form of the triangle inequality can be used to bound the minimum and maximum similarity of two objects A and B if the similarities to a reference object C is already known.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] This is used for example in metric data indexing, but has also been used to accelerate spherical k-means clustering the same way the Euclidean triangle inequality has been used to accelerate regular k-means.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] A soft cosine or ("soft" similarity) between two vectors considers similarities between pairs of features.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] For example, in the field of natural language processing (NLP) the similarity among features is quite intuitive.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Features such as words, *n*-grams, or syntactic *n*-grams can be quite similar, though formally they are considered as different features in the VSM.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] For example, words "play" and "game" are different words and thus mapped to different points in VSM; yet they are semantically related.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] In case of *n*-grams or syntactic *n*-grams, Levenshtein distance can be applied (in fact, Levenshtein distance can be applied to words as well).
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] For calculating soft cosine, the matrix **s** is used to indicate similarity between features.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] It can be calculated through Levenshtein distance, WordNet similarity, or other similarity measures.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] where *sij* = similarity(feature*i*, feature*j*).
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] If there is no similarity between features (*sii* = 1, *sij* = 0 for *i* ≠ *j*), the given equation is equivalent to the conventional cosine similarity formula.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] The time complexity of this measure is quadratic, which makes it applicable to real-world tasks.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] Note that the complexity can be reduced to subquadratic.
[src:model-embeddings/cosine-similarity] An efficient implementation of such soft cosine similarity is included in the Gensim open source library.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:model-embeddings/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] A **latent space**, also known as a **latent feature space** or **embedding space**, is an embedding of a set of items within a manifold in which items resembling each other are positioned closer to one another.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Position within the latent space can be viewed as being defined by a set of latent variables that emerge from the resemblances between the objects.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] In most cases, the dimensionality of the latent space is chosen to be lower than the dimensionality of the feature space from which the data points are drawn, making the construction of a latent space an example of dimensionality reduction, which can also be viewed as a form of data compression.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Latent spaces are usually fit via machine learning, and they can then be used as feature spaces in machine learning models, including classifiers and other supervised predictors.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] The interpretation of latent spaces in machine learning models is an ongoing area of research, but achieving clear interpretations remains challenging.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] The black-box nature of these models often makes the latent space unintuitive, while its high-dimensional, complex, and nonlinear characteristics further complicate the task of understanding it.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Analysis of the latent space geometry of diffusion models reveals a fractal structure of phase transitions in the latent space, characterized by abrupt changes in the Fisher information metric.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Some visualization techniques have been developed to connect the latent space to the visual world, but there is often not a direct connection between the latent space interpretation and the model itself.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Such techniques include t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE), where the latent space is mapped to two dimensions for visualization.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Latent space distances lack physical units, so the interpretation of these distances may depend on the application.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Several embedding models have been developed to perform this transformation to create latent space embeddings given a set of data items and a similarity function.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] These models learn the embeddings by leveraging statistical techniques and machine learning algorithms.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] GloVe: GloVe (Global Vectors for Word Representation) is another widely used embedding model for NLP.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] It combines global statistical information from a corpus with local context information to learn word embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] GloVe embeddings are known for capturing both semantic and relational similarities between words.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Siamese Networks: Siamese networks are a type of neural network architecture commonly used for similarity-based embedding.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] They consist of two identical subnetworks that process two input samples and produce their respective embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Siamese networks are often used for tasks like image similarity, recommendation systems, and face recognition.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Variational Autoencoders (VAEs): VAEs are generative models that simultaneously learn to encode and decode data.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] The latent space in VAEs acts as an embedding space.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] By training VAEs on high-dimensional data, such as images or audio, the model learns to encode the data into a compact latent representation.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] VAEs are known for their ability to generate new data samples from the learned latent space.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Multimodality refers to the integration and analysis of multiple modes or types of data within a single model or framework.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Embedding multimodal data involves capturing relationships and interactions between different data types, such as images, text, audio, and structured data.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] Multimodal embedding models aim to learn joint representations that fuse information from multiple modalities, allowing for cross-modal analysis and tasks.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] These models enable applications like image captioning, visual question answering, and multimodal sentiment analysis.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] To embed multimodal data, specialized architectures such as deep multimodal networks or multimodal transformers are employed.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] These architectures combine different types of neural network modules to process and integrate information from various modalities.
[src:model-embeddings/latent-space] The resulting embeddings capture the complex relationships between different data types, facilitating multimodal analysis and understanding.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] In natural language processing, a **sentence embedding** (or document embedding) is a representation of a natural language text as a vector of numbers which encodes meaningful semantic information.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] The name stems from the initially limitations of the approach to embed sequences of text longer than a sentence, but this is not longer a limitation.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] State of the art embeddings are based on the learned hidden layer representation of dedicated sentence transformer models.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] BERT pioneered an approach involving the use of a dedicated [CLS] token prepended to the beginning of each sentence inputted into the model; the final hidden state vector of this token encodes information about the sentence and can be fine-tuned for use in sentence classification tasks.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] In practice however, BERT's sentence embedding with the [CLS] token achieves poor performance, often worse than simply averaging non-contextual word embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] SBERT later achieved superior sentence embedding performance by fine tuning BERT's [CLS] token embeddings through the usage of a siamese neural network architecture on the SNLI dataset.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Other approaches are loosely based on the idea of distributional semantics applied to sentences.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Skip-Thought trains an encoder-decoder structure for the task of neighboring sentences predictions; this has been shown to achieve worse performance than approaches such as InferSent or SBERT.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] An alternative direction is to aggregate word embeddings, such as those returned by Word2vec, into sentence embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] The most straightforward approach is to simply compute the average of word vectors, known as continuous bag-of-words (CBOW).
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] However, more elaborate solutions based on word vector quantization have also been proposed.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] One such approach is the vector of locally aggregated word embeddings (VLAWE), which demonstrated performance improvements in downstream text classification tasks.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] In recent years, sentence embedding has seen a growing level of interest due to its applications in natural language queryable knowledge bases through the usage of vector indexing for semantic search.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] LangChain for instance utilizes sentence transformers for purposes of indexing documents.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] In particular, an indexing is generated by generating embeddings for chunks of documents and storing (document chunk, embedding) tuples.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Then given a query in natural language, the embedding for the query can be generated.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] A top k similarity search algorithm is then used between the query embedding and the document chunk embeddings to retrieve the most relevant document chunks as context information for question answering tasks.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] This approach is also known formally as retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Though not as predominant as BERTScore, sentence embeddings are commonly used for sentence similarity evaluation which sees common use for the task of optimizing a Large language model's generation parameters is often performed via comparing candidate sentences against reference sentences.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] By using the cosine-similarity of the sentence embeddings of candidate and reference sentences as the evaluation function, a grid-search algorithm can be utilized to automate hyperparameter optimization.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Multiple approaches exists for evaluating the quality of sentence embeddings typically covering one or multiple of the use-cases on models.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Some seek to measure whether the embedding is semantically meaningful by testing if semantically similar sentences appear closer together, while other sentence similarity or if embeddings reflect entailment using corpora such as Sentences Involving Compositional Knowledge (SICK), STS Bencmark.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Other approaches seek to measure the quality of the embeddings by how well it performs for downstream use-cases such as clustering, classification or semantic search.
[src:model-embeddings/sentence-embedding] Comprehensive frameworks such as BEIR or MTEB that encapsulates multiple of these approaches have since become the standard to evaluate the quality of embedding across domains and/or languages.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In natural language processing, a **word embedding** is a representation of a word.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes the meaning of the word in such a way that the words that are closer in the vector space are expected to be similar in meaning.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Word embeddings can be obtained using language modeling and feature learning techniques, where words or phrases from the vocabulary are mapped to vectors of real numbers.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Methods to generate this mapping include neural networks, dimensionality reduction on the word co-occurrence matrix, probabilistic models, explainable knowledge base method, and explicit representation in terms of the context in which words appear.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Word and phrase embeddings, when used as the underlying input representation, have been shown to boost the performance in NLP tasks such as syntactic parsing and sentiment analysis.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In distributional semantics, a quantitative methodological approach for understanding meaning in observed language, word embeddings or semantic feature space models have been used as a knowledge representation for some time.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Such models aim to quantify and categorize semantic similarities between linguistic items based on their distributional properties in large samples of language data.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The underlying idea that "a word is characterized by the company it keeps" was proposed in a 1957 article by John Rupert Firth, but also has roots in the contemporaneous work on search systems and in cognitive psychology.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The first generation of semantic space models is the vector space model for information retrieval.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Such vector space models for words and their distributional data implemented in their simplest form results in a very sparse vector space of high dimensionality (cf. curse of dimensionality).
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Reducing the number of dimensions using linear algebraic methods such as singular value decomposition then led to the introduction of latent semantic analysis in the late 1980s and the random indexing approach for collecting word co-occurrence contexts.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In 2000, Bengio et al. provided in a series of papers titled "Neural probabilistic language models" to reduce the high dimensionality of word representations in contexts by "learning a distributed representation for words".
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] A study published in NeurIPS (NIPS) 2002 introduced the use of both word and document embeddings applying the method of kernel CCA to bilingual (and multi-lingual) corpora, also providing an early example of self-supervised learning of word embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Word embeddings come in two different styles, one in which words are expressed as vectors of co-occurring words, and another in which words are expressed as vectors of linguistic contexts in which the words occur; these different styles are studied in Lavelli et al., 2004.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Roweis and Saul published in *Science* how to use "locally linear embedding" (LLE) to discover representations of high dimensional data structures.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Most new word embedding techniques after about 2005 rely on a neural network architecture instead of more probabilistic and algebraic models, after foundational work done by Yoshua Bengio and colleagues.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The approach has been adopted by many research groups after theoretical advances in 2010 had been made on the quality of vectors and the training speed of the model, as well as after hardware advances allowed for a broader parameter space to be explored profitably.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In 2013, a team at Google led by Tomas Mikolov created word2vec, a word embedding toolkit that can train vector space models faster than previous approaches.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The word2vec approach has been widely used in experimentation and was instrumental in raising interest for word embeddings as a technology, moving the research strand out of specialised research into broader experimentation and eventually paving the way for practical application.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Historically, one of the main limitations of static word embeddings or word vector space models is that words with multiple meanings are conflated into a single representation (a single vector in the semantic space).
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In other words, polysemy and homonymy are not handled properly.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] For example, in the sentence "The club I tried yesterday was great!", it is not clear if the term *club* is related to the word sense of a *club sandwich*, *clubhouse*, *golf club*, or any other sense that *club* might have.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The necessity to accommodate multiple meanings per word in different vectors (multi-sense embeddings) is the motivation for several contributions in NLP to split single-sense embeddings into multi-sense ones.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Most approaches that produce multi-sense embeddings can be divided into two main categories for their word sense representation, i.e., unsupervised and knowledge-based.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Based on word2vec skip-gram, Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (MSSG) performs word-sense discrimination and embedding simultaneously, improving its training time, while assuming a specific number of senses for each word.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In the Non-Parametric Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (NP-MSSG) this number can vary depending on each word.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Once the words are disambiguated, they can be used in a standard word embeddings technique, so multi-sense embeddings are produced.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] MSSA architecture allows the disambiguation and annotation process to be performed recurrently in a self-improving manner.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The use of multi-sense embeddings is known to improve performance in several NLP tasks, such as part-of-speech tagging, semantic relation identification, semantic relatedness, named entity recognition and sentiment analysis.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] As of the late 2010s, contextually-meaningful embeddings such as ELMo and BERT have been developed.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Unlike static word embeddings, these embeddings are at the token-level, in that each occurrence of a word has its own embedding.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] These embeddings better reflect the multi-sense nature of words, because occurrences of a word in similar contexts are situated in similar regions of BERT's embedding space.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Word embeddings for *n-*grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications have been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of deep learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The results presented by Asgari and Mofrad suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Word embeddings with applications in game design have been proposed by Rabii and Cook as a way to discover emergent gameplay using logs of gameplay data.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The process requires transcribing actions that occur during a game within a formal language and then using the resulting text to create word embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The results presented by Rabii and Cook suggest that the resulting vectors can capture expert knowledge about games like chess that are not explicitly stated in the game's rules.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] The idea has been extended to embeddings of entire sentences or even documents, e.g. in the form of the thought vectors concept.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] In 2015, some researchers suggested "skip-thought vectors" as a means to improve the quality of machine translation.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] A more recent and popular approach for representing sentences is Sentence-BERT, or SentenceTransformers, which modifies pre-trained BERT with the use of siamese and triplet network structures.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Software for training and using word embeddings includes Tomáš Mikolov's Word2vec, Stanford University's GloVe, GN-GloVe, Flair embeddings, AllenNLP's ELMo, BERT, fastText, Gensim, Indra, and Deeplearning4j.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Principal Component Analysis (PCA), Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP), and T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding (t-SNE) are used to reduce the dimensionality of word vector spaces and visualize word embeddings and clusters.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] For instance, the fastText is also used to calculate word embeddings for text corpora in Sketch Engine that are available online.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Word embeddings may contain the biases and stereotypes contained in the trained dataset, as Bolukbasi et al. points out in the 2016 paper "Man is to Computer Programmer as Woman is to Homemaker?
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] For example, one of the analogies generated using the aforementioned word embedding is "man is to computer programmer as woman is to homemaker".
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Research done by Jieyu Zhao et al. shows that the applications of these trained word embeddings without careful oversight likely perpetuates existing bias in society, which is introduced through unaltered training data.
[src:model-embeddings/word-embedding] Furthermore, word embeddings can even amplify these biases.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Word2vec represents a word as a high-dimension vector of numbers which capture relationships between words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In particular, words which appear in similar contexts are mapped to vectors which are nearby as measured by cosine similarity.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This indicates the level of semantic similarity between the words, so for example the vectors for *walk* and *ran* are nearby, as are those for "but" and "however", and "Berlin" and "Germany".
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Word2vec is a group of related models that are used to produce word embeddings.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] These models are shallow, two-layer neural networks that are trained to reconstruct linguistic contexts of words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Word2vec takes as its input a large corpus of text and produces a mapping of the set of words to a vector space, typically of several hundred dimensions, with each unique word in the corpus being assigned a vector in the space.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Word2vec can use either of two model architectures to produce these distributed representations of words: continuous bag of words (CBOW) or continuously sliding skip-gram.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In both architectures, word2vec considers both individual words and a sliding context window as it iterates over the corpus.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The CBOW can be viewed as a 'fill in the blank' task, where the word embedding represents the way the word influences the relative probabilities of other words in the context window.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Words which are semantically similar should influence these probabilities in similar ways, because semantically similar words should be used in similar contexts.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The order of context words does not influence prediction (bag of words assumption).
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In the continuous skip-gram architecture, the model uses the current word to predict the surrounding window of context words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The skip-gram architecture weighs nearby context words more heavily than more distant context words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] According to the authors' note, CBOW is faster while skip-gram does a better job for infrequent words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] After the model is trained, the learned word embeddings are positioned in the vector space such that words that share common contexts in the corpus — that is, words that are semantically and syntactically similar — are located close to one another in the space.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] More dissimilar words are located farther from one another in the space.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Both CBOW and skip-gram are methods to learn one vector per word appearing in the corpus.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Let V ("vocabulary") be the set of all words appearing in the corpus C .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Our goal is to learn one vector $v_{w}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ for each word $w\in V$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The idea of skip-gram is that the vector of a word should be close to the vector of each of its neighbors.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The idea of CBOW is that the vector-sum of a word's neighbors should be close to the vector of the word.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The idea of CBOW is to represent each word with a vector, such that it is possible to predict a word using the sum of the vectors of its neighbors.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Specifically, for each word $w_{i}$ in the corpus, the one-hot encoding of the word is used as the input to the neural network.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The output of the neural network is a probability distribution over the dictionary, representing a prediction of individual words in the neighborhood of $w_{i}$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The objective of training is to maximize $\sum _{i}\ln \Pr(w_{i}\mid w_{i+j}\colon j\in N)$ where N is a set of (non-zero) indices representing the relative locations of nearby words considered to be in $w_{i}$ 's neighborhood.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] For example, if we want each word in the corpus to be predicted by every other word in a small span of 4 words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In standard bag-of-words, a word's context is represented by a word-count (aka a word histogram) of its neighboring words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] For example, the "sat" in "the cat sat on the mat" is represented as {"the": 2, "cat": 1, "on": 1}.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Note that the last word "mat" is not used to represent "sat", because it is outside the neighborhood $N=\{-2,-1,+1,+2\}$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In continuous bag-of-words, the histogram is multiplied by a matrix V to obtain a continuous representation of the word's context.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The matrix V is also called a **dictionary**.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] It has D columns, where D is the size of the dictionary.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Let d be the length of each word vector.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] We have $V\in \mathbb {R} ^{d\times D}$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This is then multiplied with another matrix $V'$ of shape $\mathbb {R} ^{D\times d}$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This results in a vector of length D , one entry per dictionary entry.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Then, apply the softmax to obtain a probability distribution over the dictionary.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This system can be visualized as a neural network, similar in spirit to an autoencoder, of architecture linear-linear-softmax, as depicted in the diagram.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The system is trained by gradient descent to minimize the cross-entropy loss.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Once such a system is trained, we have two trained matrices $V,V'$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Either the column vectors of V or the row vectors of $V'$ can serve as the dictionary.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] For example, the word "sat" can be represented as either the "sat"-th column of V or the "sat"-th row of $V'$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] It is also possible to simply define $V'=V^{\top }$ , in which case there would no longer be a choice.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The idea of skip-gram is to represent each word with a vector, such that it is possible to predict the vectors of its neighbors using the vector of a word.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The architecture is still linear-linear-softmax, the same as CBOW, but the input and the output are switched.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The objective of training is to maximize $\sum _{i}\sum _{j\in N}\ln \Pr(w_{j+i}\mid w_{i})$ .
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Essentially, skip-gram and CBOW are exactly the same in architecture.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] They only differ in the objective function during training.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] During the 1980s, there were some early attempts at using neural networks to represent words and concepts as vectors.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In 2010, Tomáš Mikolov (then at Brno University of Technology) with co-authors applied a simple recurrent neural network with a single hidden layer to language modelling.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Word2vec was created, patented, and published in 2013 by a team of researchers led by Mikolov at Google over two papers.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The original paper was rejected by reviewers for ICLR conference 2013.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] It also took months for the code to be approved for open-sourcing.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Other researchers helped analyse and explain the algorithm.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Embedding vectors created using the Word2vec algorithm have some advantages compared to earlier algorithms such as those using n-grams and latent semantic analysis.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] GloVe was developed by a team at Stanford specifically as a competitor, and the original paper noted multiple improvements of GloVe over word2vec.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Mikolov argued that the comparison was unfair as GloVe was trained on more data, and that the fastText project showed that word2vec is superior when trained on the same data.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] As of 2022, the straight Word2vec approach was described as "dated".
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Transformer-based models, such as ELMo and BERT, which add multiple neural-network attention layers on top of a word embedding model similar to Word2vec, have come to be regarded as the state of the art in natural language processing.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Results of word2vec training can be sensitive to parametrization.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The following are some important parameters in word2vec training.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] A word2vec model can be trained with hierarchical softmax and/or negative sampling.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] To approximate the conditional log-likelihood a model seeks to maximize, the hierarchical softmax method uses a Huffman tree to reduce calculation.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The negative sampling method, on the other hand, approaches the maximization problem by minimizing the log-likelihood of sampled negative instances.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] According to the authors, hierarchical softmax works better for infrequent words while negative sampling works better for frequent words and better with low dimensional vectors.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] As training epochs increase, hierarchical softmax stops being useful.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] High-frequency and low-frequency words often provide little information.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Words with a frequency above a certain threshold, or below a certain threshold, may be subsampled or removed to speed up training.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Quality of word embedding increases with higher dimensionality.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] But after reaching some point, marginal gain diminishes.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Typically, the dimensionality of the vectors is set to be between 100 and 1,000.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The size of the context window determines how many words before and after a given word are included as context words of the given word.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] According to the authors' note, the recommended value is 10 for skip-gram and 5 for CBOW.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] There are a variety of extensions to word2vec.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] doc2vec estimates the distributed representations of documents much like how word2vec estimates representations of words: doc2vec utilizes either of two model architectures, both of which are allegories to the architectures used in word2vec.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The first, Distributed Memory Model of Paragraph Vectors (PV-DM), is identical to CBOW other than it also provides a unique document identifier as a piece of additional context.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The second architecture, Distributed Bag of Words version of Paragraph Vector (PV-DBOW), is identical to the skip-gram model except that it attempts to predict the window of surrounding context words from the paragraph identifier instead of the current word.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] doc2vec also has the ability to capture the semantic 'meanings' for additional pieces of 'context' around words; doc2vec can estimate the semantic embeddings for speakers or speaker attributes, groups, and periods of time.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] For example, doc2vec has been used to estimate the political positions of political parties in various Congresses and Parliaments in the U.S. and U.K., respectively, and various governmental institutions.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Another extension of word2vec is top2vec, which leverages both document and word embeddings to estimate distributed representations of topics. top2vec takes document embeddings learned from a doc2vec model and reduces them into a lower dimension (typically using UMAP).
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The space of documents is then scanned using HDBSCAN, and clusters of similar documents are found.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Next, the centroid of documents identified in a cluster is considered to be that cluster's topic vector.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Finally, top2vec searches the semantic space for word embeddings located near to the topic vector to ascertain the 'meaning' of the topic.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The word with embeddings most similar to the topic vector might be assigned as the topic's title, whereas far away word embeddings may be considered unrelated.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] As opposed to other topic models such as LDA, top2vec provides canonical 'distance' metrics between two topics, or between a topic and another embeddings (word, document, or otherwise).
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Together with results from HDBSCAN, users can generate topic hierarchies, or groups of related topics and subtopics.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Furthermore, a user can use the results of top2vec to infer the topics of out-of-sample documents.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] After inferring the embedding for a new document, must only search the space of topics for the closest topic vector.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] An extension of word vectors for n-grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications has been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of machine learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The results suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] A similar variant, dna2vec, has shown that there is correlation between Needleman–Wunsch similarity score and cosine similarity of dna2vec word vectors.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] An extension of word vectors for creating a dense vector representation of unstructured radiology reports has been proposed by Banerjee et al.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] One of the biggest challenges with Word2vec is how to handle unknown or out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words and morphologically similar words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] If the Word2vec model has not encountered a particular word before, it will be forced to use a random vector, which is generally far from its ideal representation.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This can particularly be an issue in domains like medicine where synonyms and related words can be used depending on the preferred style of radiologist, and words may have been used infrequently in a large corpus.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Of particular interest, the IWE model (trained on the one institutional dataset) successfully translated to a different institutional dataset which demonstrates good generalizability of the approach across institutions.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The reasons for successful word embedding learning in the word2vec framework are poorly understood.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Goldberg and Levy point out that the word2vec objective function causes words that occur in similar contexts to have similar embeddings (as measured by cosine similarity) and note that this is in line with J.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] However, they note that this explanation is "very hand-wavy" and argue that a more formal explanation would be preferable.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] (2015) show that much of the superior performance of word2vec or similar embeddings in downstream tasks is not a result of the models per se, but of the choice of specific hyperparameters.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Transferring these hyperparameters to more 'traditional' approaches yields similar performances in downstream tasks.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] (2016) explain word2vec and related algorithms as performing inference for a simple generative model for text, which involves a random walk generation process based upon loglinear topic model.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] They use this to explain some properties of word embeddings, including their use to solve analogies.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The word embedding approach is able to capture multiple different degrees of similarity between words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] (2013) found that semantic and syntactic patterns can be reproduced using vector arithmetic.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Such relationships can be generated for a range of semantic relations (such as Country–Capital) as well as syntactic relations (e.g. present tense–past tense).
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This facet of word2vec has been exploited in a variety of other contexts.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] For example, word2vec has been used to map a vector space of words in one language to a vector space constructed from another language.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Relationships between translated words in both spaces can be used to assist with machine translation of new words.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] (2013) developed an approach to assessing the quality of a word2vec model which draws on the semantic and syntactic patterns discussed above.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] They developed a set of 8,869 semantic relations and 10,675 syntactic relations which they use as a benchmark to test the accuracy of a model.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] When assessing the quality of a vector model, a user may draw on this accuracy test which is implemented in word2vec, or develop their own test set which is meaningful to the corpora which make up the model.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] This approach offers a more challenging test than simply arguing that the words most similar to a given test word are intuitively plausible.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] The use of different model parameters and different corpus sizes can greatly affect the quality of a word2vec model.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Accuracy can be improved in a number of ways, including the choice of model architecture (CBOW or Skip-Gram), increasing the training data set, increasing the number of vector dimensions, and increasing the window size of words considered by the algorithm.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Each of these improvements comes with the cost of increased computational complexity and therefore increased model generation time.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] In models using large corpora and a high number of dimensions, the skip-gram model yields the highest overall accuracy, and consistently produces the highest accuracy on semantic relationships, as well as yielding the highest syntactic accuracy in most cases.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] However, the CBOW is less computationally expensive and yields similar accuracy results.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Overall, accuracy increases with the number of words used and the number of dimensions.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Mikolov et al. report that doubling the amount of training data results in an increase in computational complexity equivalent to doubling the number of vector dimensions.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Altszyler and coauthors (2017) studied Word2vec performance in two semantic tests for different corpus size.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] They found that Word2vec has a steep learning curve, outperforming another word-embedding technique, latent semantic analysis (LSA), when it is trained with medium to large corpus size (more than 10 million words).
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] However, with a small training corpus, LSA showed better performance.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Additionally they show that the best parameter setting depends on the task and the training corpus.
[src:model-embeddings/word2vec] Nevertheless, for skip-gram models trained in medium size corpora, with 50 dimensions, a window size of 15 and 10 negative samples seems to be a good parameter setting.
